  "texts": [
    "Audit summaries with key findings must become publicly accessible.",
    "Additionally, heightened due diligence obligations require VLOPs to bolster identity verification, external vetting of policies, and coordinated oversight across EU member states through a European Board for Digital Services [52].",
    "Graduated responsibilities extend to smaller platforms as well, including accessible reporting procedures for illegal content.To enable explicit mapping between key DSA mechanisms and subsequent critiques and research directions, core provisions are coded by unique abbreviations as summarized in Table 1.",
    "These mechanism codes will be referenced throughout the text where relevant.",
    "DSA interventions for AI governanceWhile not positioning itself as an \"AI regulator\" outrightas expected by the EU's AI Act [37]-specific DSA transparency provisions granting external data access, requiring recurring independent audits evaluating algorithmic systems, mandating systemic risk assessments, and restricting manipulative \"dark patterns\" (Art.25) align closely with emerging policy needs around accountable and ethical AI.Rather than examining individual AI applications in isolation, it is more constructive to review promising pathways the DSA establishes to institute sustained external oversight and accountability over influential algorithmic systems across sectors."
  ],
